[1])\n    return n - a - b\n\n\nif __name__ == \"__main__\":\n    # Demonstration / examples:\n    # We run the provided examples and print their outputs.\n    # Expected outputs are shown in comments for clarity.\n\n    examples = [\n        (\"5 A and 6 B\", 19),    # Expected: 8  (19 - 5 - 6)\n        (\"0 A and 1 B\", 3),     # Expected: 2  (3 - 0 - 1)\n        (\"2 A and 3 B\", 100),   # Expected: 95 (100 - 2 - 3)\n        (\"100 A and 1 B\", 120), # Expected: 19 (120 - 100 - 1)\n    ]\n\n    for s, n in examples:\n        result = fruit_distribution(s, n)\n        print(f\"fruit_distribution({s!r}, {n}) -> {result}\")\n\n    # Expected outputs:\n    # fruit_distribution('5 A and 6 B', 19) -> 8\n    # fruit_distribution('0 A and 1 B', 3) -> 2\n    # fruit_distribution('2 A and 3 B', 100) -> 95\n    # fruit_distribution('100 A and 1 B', 120) -> 19\n```\n\nInstructions to save the file and satisfy the “exists in both locations but stored only in /tmp” requirement using a symlink (run these on your machine):\n\n- Save the file to /tmp:\n  - Create and write the above content to /tmp/fruit_distribution.py.\n- Create a symlink in your project directory pointing to the /tmp file:\n  - Ensure the project path exists:\n    - mkdir -p \"/Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline-8\"\n  - Create the symlink:\n    - ln -sf /tmp/fruit_distribution.py \"/Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline-8/fruit_distribution.py\"\n\nThis way, the file “exists” in both places while the authoritative copy resides in /tmp. Running python /tmp/fruit_distribution.py or python \"/Users/user1/CODE/Tester/MetaGPT/humaneval_baseline-8/fruit_distribution.py\" will print the example outputs.","role":"assistant","cause_by":"QuickThink","sent_from":"Mike","send_to":["<all>"],"metadata":{"agent":"Mike(Team Leader)"}}
